\description{
Estimates interrater-reliability intraclass correlation coefficients (ICCs)
from a fitted linear mixed model, rather than from classical ANOVA mean
squares. \code{icc()} computes the two-way \strong{absolute-agreement} (\verb{ICC(A,*)}) or
\strong{consistency} (\verb{ICC(C,*)}) coefficients of McGraw & Wong (1996), for a
single rater (\verb{ICC(*,1)}) or the mean of \code{k} raters (\verb{ICC(*,k)}), treating the
raters as a random sample (Case 2) or as fixed (Case 3).
}
\section{Which ICC is this, and when should you use it?}{

Three choices pin down the coefficient:
\itemize{
\item \strong{Agreement vs. consistency} (\code{type}). \strong{Absolute agreement} treats
systematic differences between raters (the rater main effect,
\eqn{\sigma^2_r}) as error: use it when the actual value matters and raters
must agree on the number (clinical scores, measurements). \strong{Consistency}
ignores a constant per-rater offset: use it when only relative standing
matters. A large gap between the two signals big systematic differences in
rater level -- a rating-procedure problem worth fixing.
\item \strong{Single vs. average} (\code{unit}). \strong{\verb{ICC(*,1)}} is the reliability of a
\emph{single} rater; \strong{\verb{ICC(*,k)}} is the reliability of the \emph{mean} of your \code{k}
raters. Report \verb{ICC(*,k)} when the averaged score is what you will use.
\item \strong{Random vs. fixed raters} (\code{raters}). \strong{Random} treats your raters as a
sample you wish to generalize beyond -- the recommended default for
interrater reliability. \strong{Fixed} treats them as the only raters of interest
and forgoes generalization; it is fit separately (raters as fixed effects),
so on balanced data it matches the random point estimate but on incomplete
data it genuinely differs. \code{icc()} warns when you choose it. Fixed-rater
consistency is the classic Shrout & Fleiss \code{ICC(3,1)}.
}
}

\section{Estimand}{

With a single rating per subject-by-rater cell, the subject-by-rater
interaction and pure error are not separately identified; only their sum, the
residual variance \eqn{\sigma^2_{res}}, is estimable. Absolute agreement counts
the rater main effect \eqn{\sigma^2_r} as error; consistency drops it:
\deqn{ICC(A,1) = \sigma^2_s / (\sigma^2_s + \sigma^2_r + \sigma^2_{res})}
\deqn{ICC(A,k) = \sigma^2_s / (\sigma^2_s + (\sigma^2_r + \sigma^2_{res}) / k)}
\deqn{ICC(C,1) = \sigma^2_s / (\sigma^2_s + \sigma^2_{res})}
\deqn{ICC(C,k) = \sigma^2_s / (\sigma^2_s + \sigma^2_{res} / k)}
where \eqn{\sigma^2_s} is the subject (signal) variance and \code{k} is the number
of raters.
}

\section{Multilevel designs (subject vs. cluster level)}{

When subjects are nested in higher-level clusters (pupils in classrooms,
patients in clinics), single-level ICCs conflate the levels and are biased
(ten Hove et al. 2022). Supplying \code{cluster} fits the five-component Design-1
model
\deqn{score \sim 1 + (1|cluster) + (1|cluster{:}subject) + (1|rater) + (1|cluster{:}rater)}
and reports two distinct reliabilities. The \strong{subject level} (within-cluster)
asks how reliably raters distinguish subjects \emph{within} a cluster: its signal is
the between-subject-within-cluster variance and cluster variance drops out. The
\strong{cluster level} (between-cluster) asks how reliably raters distinguish cluster
means: its signal is the between-cluster variance and the rater-disagreement
error is the cluster-by-rater term. Choose the level that matches the decision
you will make (about a subject, or about a cluster). The agreement/consistency
and single/average choices above apply at each level.

\code{level = "conflated"} reports the \strong{biased single-level ICC} you would get by
\emph{ignoring} the clustering (ten Hove et al. 2022, Eq. 14): between- and
within-cluster subject variance are both counted as signal, and the rater-related
terms as error. It is offered only as a \strong{diagnostic contrast} -- to quantify how
much the nesting distorts reliability -- and is never a recommended coefficient;
\code{print()} flags it as such. It is the \strong{flat two-way ICC} read off the multilevel
fit, so it comes in both \code{type} forms: absolute agreement (Eq. 14) and
\strong{consistency} (which drops the rater main-effect variance, McGraw & Wong 1996).
It needs a crossed (Design 1) random-rater design and works on both balanced and
\strong{incomplete} data (same \code{k_eff} divisor). Because it reads the cluster-by-rater
variance, it needs raters that bridge clusters; without bridging the conflated
level is dropped (like the cluster level). Request it alongside the correct levels,
e.g. \code{level = c("subject", "cluster", "conflated")}.

The design is \strong{inferred from the data} (ten Hove et al. 2022, Table 2). If
raters are crossed with clusters (each rater rates in every cluster) the
five-component model above is used (Design 1). Because the design is read from
the rater \strong{labels}, a rater label that appears in more than one cluster is
taken to be the \emph{same} rater (crossed). If your raters are cluster-specific but
share labels (e.g. "rater 1"/"rater 2" reused in every cluster -- a nested
design), give them cluster-unique labels or declare \code{design = "nested_in_clusters"};
otherwise the design is treated as crossed and \code{icc()} prints a one-time note of
that assumption. If raters are \strong{nested in
clusters} (each cluster has its own raters; Design 2) a four-component model is
fit, with the rater variance carried by the nested rater-within-cluster term. If
raters are \strong{nested in subjects} (each subject has its own raters; Design 3) the
rater variance is confounded into the residual, giving a three-component
multilevel \emph{one-way} model that reports agreement-only \code{ICC(1)}/\code{ICC(k)}. Both
nested designs define only the \strong{subject} level -- a cluster-level ICC needs
raters crossed with clusters -- so \code{level} is restricted to \code{"subject"} for them.
Mixed patterns (some raters crossed, some nested) are not a supported design and
raise an error. The \strong{crossed} design (Design 1) additionally supports
\strong{incomplete} data -- subjects rated by different, overlapping rater subsets
(missing cells) -- computing the subject-level ICCs by REML with the averaging
divisor set to the effective number of ratings per subject (\code{k_eff}, the harmonic
mean), exactly as the single-level incomplete two-way ICC does. Identifiability is
checked first: each cluster's subject-by-rater layout must be connected, and for
absolute agreement raters must bridge clusters (otherwise the design is really
rater-nested). When missing cells make the crossed-vs-nested pattern ambiguous,
declare it with \code{design} (above). On incomplete data the \strong{cluster} level is
reported (when raters bridge clusters) as both the single-rater \code{ICC(c,1)} and the
averaged \code{ICC(c,k)}: the average divides the cluster error by the effective number
of raters behind each cluster's observed (cells-pooled) mean, the inverse-Simpson
harmonic \code{k_c^eff} (reported as \code{k_c_eff}; equal to the rater count on complete
data). A rater-balanced cluster mean would have a different (higher) effective
count. This averaged cluster \code{ICC(c,k)} on incomplete data ships for every
random-rater engine -- \code{glmmTMB}, \code{lme4}, and \code{brms} (the divisor is applied to the
posterior draws' variance components exactly as for the frequentist fits). \strong{Fixed
raters}
(\code{raters = "fixed"}) are supported for the crossed design at the \strong{subject} level
on both balanced and \strong{incomplete} data: the rater main effect becomes the
finite-population variance of the observed raters (McGraw & Wong Case 3A), so on
balanced data consistency is identical to the random-rater case and absolute
agreement differs only by that term; on incomplete data both types differ from
random (the finite-population variance is read from the ragged rater-contrast fit).
\strong{Nested (Design 2) fixed raters} are likewise supported at the \strong{subject} level on
both balanced and \strong{incomplete} data (the finite-population rater variance is formed
\strong{per cluster} -- each cluster's own raters -- and averaged over clusters; on ragged
data each cluster uses its own effective rater count). The fixed-rater \strong{cluster}
level is supported for the crossed (Design 1) design on \strong{balanced, complete} data
(signal \eqn{\sigma^2_c}, agreement error the finite-population \eqn{\theta^2_r} plus
the cluster-by-rater term \eqn{\sigma^2_{cr}}); on balanced data it equals the
random-rater cluster-level ICC. The Bayesian (\code{engine = "brms"}) fixed-rater
\strong{cluster} level is likewise supported for the crossed (Design 1) design on
balanced, complete data, and the Bayesian incomplete/ragged fixed-rater \strong{nested}
(Design 2) subject level is supported too. Incomplete/unbalanced fixed-rater
cluster-level estimation and Design-3 fixed raters (nested in subjects -- no
separable rater effect) remain for later milestones.
}

\section{Within-cell replicates}{

When a subject-by-rater cell is rated \strong{more than once} (within-cell
replicates), \code{icc()} fits the two-way random model \strong{with a subject-by-rater
interaction}, \code{score ~ 1 + (1|subject) + (1|rater) + (1|subject:rater)}, which
splits the single-rating residual into the \strong{interaction} \eqn{\sigma^2_{sr}}
(does a rater systematically rate a subject high or low -- stable disagreement?)
and \strong{pure error} \eqn{\sigma^2_e} (rating noise). Both are reported. The
single-occasion ICCs are unchanged in value from a one-rating-per-cell analysis
(a single rating's error still includes the interaction), but the components are
no longer confounded, and \code{occasions = "average"} reports the reliability of the
mean of the replicates (which reduces \eqn{\sigma^2_e} but not
\eqn{\sigma^2_{sr}}). With \code{raters = "fixed"} the rater main effect becomes the
finite-population \eqn{\theta^2_r} (McGraw & Wong Case 3A, fit as
\code{score ~ 1 + rater + (1|subject) + (1|subject:rater)}); on balanced, complete data
\eqn{\theta^2_r = \sigma^2_r}, so fixed reproduces the random-rater coefficients.
\strong{Multilevel} replicated designs add a \code{(1|cluster:subject:rater)} term (crossed
Design 1 and nested Design 2), splitting the highest-order residual at the subject
level. \strong{Ragged} (unequal per-cell counts or missing cells) two-way random data
fits the \strong{single-occasion} family directly (the replicate analogue of an
incomplete design); the occasion-averaged coefficient on ragged data is not yet
supported (there is no single effective occasion count to average over). One-way
replicates, fixed or multilevel ragged replicates, and \code{d_study()} projection off a
replicate fit are planned for later milestones.
}

\section{Confidence intervals}{

Intervals are Monte-Carlo: parameters are drawn from the fitted covariance on
the model's internal (log) scale and back-transformed, so the interval is
boundary-aware near the common zero-rater-variance case where the delta method
fails. Pass \code{seed} for a reproducible interval.
}

\section{The \code{"npbootstrap"} interval (one-way)}{
For \code{unit = "average"} (the ICC(k), reliability of the mean of the \emph{k} ratings)
the transformed bootstrap-\emph{t} interval is the exact monotone \strong{Spearman-Brown}
image of the single-rating ICC(1) interval, \code{g(rho) = k*rho / (1 + (k-1)*rho)}
applied to the two ICC(1) endpoints. Because that map is strictly increasing, the
ICC(k) interval's coverage is \strong{identical to the ICC(1) interval's, by
construction} -- it is not a separate approximation.

On \strong{unbalanced} data (unequal ratings per subject) the reducer uses the ANOVA
effective group size \code{n0 = (N - sum(n_i^2)/N) / (k - 1)} (Ohyama 2025) in the
\verb{log F} transform, and studentizes \code{log(SSA) - log(SSE)} -- the pivot the
infinitesimal-jackknife SE is derived for (Ukoumunne et al. 2003, Appendix A),
which coincides with the balanced \verb{log F} pivot when subjects are equally rated.
Only \code{unit = "single"} (ICC(1)) is available unbalanced; the ICC(k) average is
balanced-only for now (its unbalanced averaging divisor is not yet resolved).

Following Ukoumunne et al. (2003, Â§5.2), the endpoints are \strong{not truncated} to
\verb{[0, 1]}: they are confined only to the estimator's own support (approaching
\code{-1/(n0-1)} from above for ICC(1), and unbounded below for ICC(k)), so a
near-boundary lower endpoint can be negative -- markedly so for ICC(k). Leaving
them untruncated is what makes the coverage faithful to the published method.

The reported \strong{point estimate} is the engine (REML) point, exactly as for every
other \code{ci_method} -- \code{ci_method} selects the interval, not the estimator. At the
zero-between-variance boundary the point reads \code{0} while the untruncated interval
may extend below \code{0}; this is the normal picture for a boundary-respecting point
beside an honest interval, and it signals that the data are consistent with values
near and below zero.
}

\section{The classical \code{"searle"} and \code{"burch"} intervals (balanced one-way)}{
Both are deterministic closed forms from the one-way ANOVA. \code{"searle"} inverts the
exact-F pivot \code{F / (1 + n*lambda) ~ F(k-1, k(n-1))} (Searle 1971; the McGraw & Wong
1996 Table 7 limits); it is exact under normality. \code{"burch"} builds
kurtosis-adjusted \code{log(1 + n*theta-hat)} limits (Burch 2011), so its width tracks
the data's tail weight -- wider but robust to non-normality, and never
under-covering. Both share the conventions above: the \code{unit = "average"} (ICC(k))
interval is the same exact monotone \strong{Spearman-Brown} image of the ICC(1)
endpoints (so its coverage is identical by construction), endpoints are left
\strong{untruncated} on the estimator's own support, and the reported \strong{point} is the
engine (REML) point. Being closed forms they take no \code{mc_samples}, \code{boot_samples},
or \code{seed}, and report no \code{std.error} (there is no sampling distribution). Their
value is a finite, well-calibrated interval on the near-zero-ICC boundary where the
Monte-Carlo default aborts.
}

